      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To solve this problem within the given constraints, you can use a sliding window approach combined with a hash map to keep track of the sums and their corresponding indices. This way, you can efficiently find the longest subarray with a perfect square sum without exceeding the memory limit.\n\nHere's a Python solution that should work:\n\n```python\ndef is_perfect_square(x):\n    s = int(x**0.5)\n    return s * s == x\n\ndef longest_subarray_with_perfect_square_sum(arr):\n    from collections import defaultdict\n\n    n = len(arr)\n    max_len = 0\n    sum_map = defaultdict(int)\n    sum_map[0] = -1  # To handle the case where the subarray starts from index 0\n    current_sum = 0\n\n    for i in range(n):\n        current_sum += arr[i]\n\n        if is_perfect_square(current_sum):\n            max_len = max(max_len, i - sum_map[current_sum])\n\n        if current_sum in sum_map:\n            max_len = max(max_len, i - sum_map[current_sum])\n\n        sum_map[current_sum] = i\n\n    return max_len\n\n# Example usage:\narr = [1, 2, 3,",
